### 🔴 HIGH Severity

#### 1. Conditional Test Logic (Smell #1)

**Method:** `ProcessOrder_SetsCorrectStatus` (line 24)

```csharp
if (result.TotalAmount > 100)
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
else
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
```

**Risk:** One branch is never exercised — the test always passes regardless of which status is returned. A bug in either path is invisible.

**Fix — split into two deterministic tests:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_StandardAmount_SetsStandardStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_PremiumAmount_SetsPremiumStatus()
{
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-EXPENSIVE", 5) } };
    var result = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory).ProcessOrder(order);
    Assert.AreEqual("PremiumProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

---

#### 2. Assertion-Free Test / Unknown Test (Smell #4)

**Method:** `ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError` (line 43)

```csharp
processor.ProcessOrder(order);
// no assertion
```

**Risk:** False confidence — test passes even if `ProcessOrder` returns garbage or corrupts state. Only an unhandled exception would surface a failure.

**Fix:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void ProcessOrder_CompletesWithoutError()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    var result = processor.ProcessOrder(order);

    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("StandardProcessed", result.Status);
}
```

---

#### 3. Sleepy Test (Smell #3)

**Method:** `ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent` (line 91)

```csharp
Thread.Sleep(2000);
```

**Risk:** Non-deterministic — on slow CI the 2 s may not be enough; on fast machines it wastes wall-clock time. Contributes to flakiness (Camara et al., SAST 2021).

**Fix — use a polling/signaling approach:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public async Task ProcessOrder_AsyncNotification_IsSent()
{
    var processor = new OrderProcessor(_db, _email, _inventory);
    var order = new Order { Items = { new OrderItem("SKU-1", 1) } };

    await processor.ProcessOrderAsync(order);

    Assert.IsTrue(_email.WasNotificationSent(order.Id));
}
```

If the API is fire-and-forget, use `_email.WaitForNotification(order.Id, timeout: TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))` backed by a `TaskCompletionSource`.

